Epoch:0 | TOPIC | Scientist1:The proposal centers on investigating whether feature-based interpretability methods (e.g., LIME, SHAP, Integrated Gradients) produce consistent attributions across neural text classifiers that are functionally equivalent but trained with different random initializations. Despite identical performance, such models may learn different internal representations—a phenomenon known as solution non-identifiability—potentially leading to divergent explanations. This raises concerns about the reliability of current interpretability tools in high-stakes domains.

The proposed study would involve training multiple BERT-style models on standard datasets (e.g., SST-2, AG News) with varied random seeds, confirming functional equivalence via accuracy and prediction agreement, then applying several attribution methods. Attribution divergence would be measured using rank correlation, Jaccard similarity of top-k tokens, and Wasserstein distance over saliency maps. To understand the source of instability, representational differences would be analyzed using probing classifiers or representational similarity analysis (RSA).

The research aims to determine whether explanation inconsistencies stem from superficial noise or deeper representational variance, thereby assessing the trustworthiness of existing interpretability techniques. Findings could challenge current practices in ML explainability and guide the development of more robust, stable methods—or identify which existing methods are reliably invariant to training randomness.
