  "Idea": "This paper introduces a paradigm shift in the evaluation and construction of feature-based interpretability methods for neural text classifiers by proposing a new framework called Invariant Rationalization via Semantic Subspace Alignment (IR-SSA). Rather than merely quantifying attribution instability across differently initialized models—as prior work does—we ask whether it is possible to *learn* explanations that are provably invariant to architectural stochasticity while preserving semantic fidelity. We argue that current interpretability methods fail not necessarily because they are inherently noisy, but because they lack explicit constraints to align their outputs with stable, underlying semantic manifolds. To address this, we develop a meta-learning framework that trains a lightweight rationalizer network to generate token-level attributions by distilling invariant semantic signals from ensembles of functionally equivalent transformer classifiers. These classifiers are constructed using optimal transport-based weight alignment to ensure identical input-output behavior despite divergent parameter realizations. The rationalizer is trained using a dual objective: (1) faithfulness to each model's predictions via gradient matching loss, and (2) invariance across models via a contrastive regularization term that minimizes attribution divergence on semantically similar inputs while maximizing it on discriminative ones. Central to our approach is the Class-Consistent Semantic Vector (CCSV), inspired by DISK-CSV, which captures directionally aligned representations in the final-layer embedding space across models and serves as a canonical reference for grounding interpretations. We further introduce the Attribution Invariance Score (AIS), a normalized metric that quantifies the degree to which an explanation remains stable across functionally equivalent models relative to a baseline of random-parameter networks. Through extensive experiments on SST-2, AG News, and Toxic Comments datasets, we demonstrate that IR-SSA produces significantly more stable attributions than raw application of Integrated Gradients, SHAP, or attention rollout—without sacrificing fidelity. Ablation studies reveal that instability in standard methods disproportionately arises from feed-forward sublayers with high Jacobian sensitivity. Human evaluation with NLP practitioners shows that IR-SSA-generated rationales lead to higher inter-annotator agreement in downstream decision-making tasks. Importantly, when applied to biased datasets (e.g., those with demographic skew), IR-SSA naturally downweights spurious correlations by virtue of its invariance prior, offering a side benefit of implicit debiasing akin to—but distinct from—Paper 3’s instance weighting. Our work thus contributes not only a novel diagnostic tool but a constructive pathway toward trustworthy, reproducible model explanations.",
