  "Idea": "This paper proposes a novel diagnostic framework to dissect the sources of instability in feature-based interpretability methods for neural text classifiers. Specifically, we investigate whether observed discrepancies in feature attributions across differently initialized models arise from genuine representational differences in how semantics are encoded (representation-induced divergence) or from instabilities inherent to the interpretation method itself (method-induced instability). To do so, we introduce a controlled experimental setup using functionally equivalent transformer-based classifiers—models that produce identical predictions on all inputs but differ in parameter space due to random initialization and stochastic optimization paths. We generate such models via post-hoc weight permutation alignment and symmetry-preserving retraining techniques derived from recent advances in neural network identifiability. Using these matched pairs, we apply multiple feature-based interpretability methods (e.g., Integrated Gradients, LIME, SHAP, attention rollout) and quantify attribution divergence using Earth Mover’s Distance and rank correlation metrics. Crucially, we contrast this with a baseline of 'random-parameter' models (as in Paper 1) and adversarially perturbed inputs (as in Paper 2), enabling us to isolate method-induced effects. We further propose a new metric, Interpretation Stability Gap (ISG), defined as the difference in average attribution divergence between functionally equivalent models and truly divergent ones. A high ISG indicates strong method-induced instability. Additionally, we analyze whether certain architectural components (e.g., attention heads, feed-forward layers) contribute disproportionately to unstable attributions via ablation studies. The significance lies in shifting the discourse from merely observing instability to diagnosing its root cause—enabling targeted improvements in interpretability methods. If our results show that even functionally identical models yield vastly different attributions, it challenges the semantic validity of current explanation techniques and suggests a need for regularization during interpretation, akin to adversarial training for robustness. Conversely, if attributions align well across equivalent models, instability in standard settings may be attributed to representational drift rather than methodological flaws. This work has broad implications for model trustworthiness in high-stakes domains like healthcare and law, where consistent, reliable explanations are essential.",
